{{DISPLAYTITLE:ACCEPT_KEYWORDS}}

'''La variable <code>ACCEPT_KEYWORDS</code> informa al gestor de paquetes qué valores [[KEYWORDS]] puede aceptar un ebuild. Esta variable normalmente se define en los [[profile|perfiles]] pero se puede obviar en el fichero {{Path|/etc/portage/make.conf}} del usuario o incluso en la línea de comandos.'''

The default value of most profiles' <code>ACCEPT_KEYWORDS</code> variable is the architecture itself, like <code>ACCEPT_KEYWORDS="amd64"</code> or <code>ACCEPT_KEYWORDS="arm"</code>. In these cases, the package manager will only accept ebuilds whose KEYWORDS variable contains this architecture. If the user wants to be able to install and work with ebuilds that are not considered production-ready yet, he can add the same architecture but with the <code>~</code> prefix to it, like so:

{{File|/etc/portage/make.conf||<pre>
ACCEPT_KEYWORDS="~amd64"
</pre>
}}

No se debe especificar la palabra clave estable (<code>amd64</code>) cuándo se añade la palabra clave para pruebas (<code>amd64</code>) ya que <code>ACCEPT_KEYWORDS</code> es una variable incremental.

It is generally considered a bad idea to override the <code>ACCEPT_KEYWORDS</code> variable on the command line, as this is not persistent and might result in unwanted behavior from the package manager.


